Pompeius, Sextus, younger son of the triumvir, escaped almost alone from the field of Munda (B.c. 45). The general confusion which followed the death of Caesar enabled him to collect a fleet, with which he established himself in Sicily. His naval forces allowed him to cut off the corn supplies from Rome, and the scarcity caused such disturbance in the capital that the triumvirs were compelled to admit Sextus into partnership at the treaty of Misenum (B.c. 39). war, however, broke out in the following year.
